ACCESS KEYS
 
Some browsers support jumping to specific links by typing keys defined on the web site. You can press ALT + an access key. You need to press ENTER after pressing the access key to follow the link.
 
All pages on this site define the following access keys:
  • Access key 1 - Home Page
  • Access key 2 - Skip Navigation (for text-only browsers)
  • Access key 3 - Site Index
  • Access key 4 - Search
  • Access key 5 - My Tools
  • Access key 6 - Help
  • Access key 7 - "Log in" or "Sign out" (depending on context)
  • Access key 8 - View Glossary (when applicable)
  • Access key 9 - Feedback
  • Access key 0 - Accessibility Statement (this document)
When a link has an access key, you can find the access key by moving your mouse over the link.
 
PRINT
 
Some blocks inside a page can be displayed independently, using the "Printable Version" link.
 
FORMS AND GLOSSARY
 
1. When you click on a label, the focus is automatically set to the associated field.
 
2. A glossary is available in most pages, describing and explaining each data element or field of the current page.
 
3. The focus is always set when forms are displayed in a page.
 
4. The tabulation order is always consistent with the layout of the form. If your browser is not compatible with this feature, the default tabulation order is close to the desirable tabulation order.
 
5. Some form labels have an underlined character. Press ALT in combination with this character to jump to the associated field.
 
LINKS, TITLE ATTRIBUTES AND JAVASCRIPT
 
1. Many links and labels have title attributes. Title attributes appear in a yellow box when you move your mouse over the link. They describe the link or label in greater detail, unless the description follows the link or label, or the context makes it obvious. The elements with a title attribute are highlighted in bold.
 
2. The links opening a new window are highlighted in italic.
 
3. For lookup windows, links are written in a way to allow non-Javascript browsers to browse their content. No Javascript is required in navigation drop-down menus.
 
UNIFORM RESOURCE LOCATORS
 
1. Most pages have a user-friendly address specifying their hierarchy and their content. Example: /references/termsofuse/.
 
2. This site includes a mechanism to redirect the users to the most current location when a page has been moved.
 
3. All pages are safe to bookmark unless specified otherwise.
 
4. When the slash character is missing at the end of a URL, this slash is automatically added.
 
IMAGES
 
1. All content images used in this site include descriptive ALT attributes. Purely decorative graphics include empty ALT attributes.
 
2. This site is not image-intensive. The size of each page is compatible with a dial-up connection.
 
VISUAL DESIGN
 
1. This site uses cascading style sheets for visual layout.
 
2. This site uses relative font sizes, compatible with the user-specified "text size" option in visual browsers. However, some fonts have fixed sizes when they are directly associated with a graphical elements, such as menus and tabs.
 
3. If your browser or browsing device does not support style sheets at all, the content of each page is still readable.
 
COOKIES
 
1. Cookies are not required to browse this site. URL-rewriting techniques are used instead when cookies are not available.
 
2. The number of cookies sent to the client is minimal. See the privacy practices for more details regarding cookies.
 
NAVIGATION
 
Each page contains a "skip navigation" link allowing text-only users to go directly to the content of the page. This link is invisible to users with a graphical browser.
 
STANDARDS COMPLIANCE
 
All pages validate XHTML 1.0 Transitional.
 
The style sheets used by this site follow the CSS format.
 
Recommendations in U.S. Section 508 Guidelines and Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 1.0 are followed. Some screens may not follow these guidelines when not practical or to address compatibility issues.
 
META INFORMATION
 
The description and the copyright of each page are specified as META tags.
